The offices also include the kindergarten, the architects understood
The Avriopoint office building in Brno is the new seat of Arch.Design.
No one would expect it to hide a mini-kindergarten with everything that goes with it - with colorful walls, imaginative furniture, a bunch of toys and even a miniature playground on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, it can be attended by the children of Arch.Design employees.
The design-architectural company Arch.Design, whose studios emerged a number of important Brno buildings, have been counting on space for its corporate mini-kinders since the first drawings of the Avriopoint building.
It employs almost 90 people, mostly in the age of a babyboom, and it was important to keep the women’s designers and architects from returning to work quickly.
Along with the possibility of part-time jobs, the nursery is a benefit that Arch.Design offers to its employees as part of the social program.
Builders and architects have the opportunity to combine demanding employment with childcare.
The mini-kindergarten was invented by Arch.Design employees themselves and with the support of management they managed to obtain a subsidy of the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The corporate mini-kinders (Companies) is funded by the European Social Fund through the Operational Programme Human Resources and Employment and the state budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to grant funding (subsidy of CZK 2, 8 million. CZK) could buy equipment and equipment and for two years provide qualified staff and operation.
After the financial subsidy is drawn up (2 years), Arch.Design is obliged to run a mini-kind for 3 years at its own expense.
The preparation of the project took one year and Economy Rating significantly helped with the application for the subsidy.
Care is provided by qualified staff, children are cared for all day by a nurse and a kindergarten teacher, so children can go to kindergarten without age restrictions, yet most of them are over 3 years old.
Because it is a "mini-kindergarten", only 5 children can be present at the same time, but more will be replaced during the day.
The operation of the nursery is flexible according to the needs of parents, and the children of all employees have the same right to use the nursery regardless of the hierarchy of the position in the company.
Although it is individual education and care, the program content in the mini-kind is comparable to the framework program of preschool education.
Children not only play here, but they are also provided with quality teaching - from basic cognition to preparation for school desks, the English language is also taught.
The class is equipped not only with toys, stimulating games, but also a computer that children can use.
The presence of young children directly in the company creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can check their child at any time and stressful situations with delayed picking up children from kindergartens away from their parents' workplaces are eliminated.
Parents use working hours more productively.
It is not surprising that a naturally loyal relationship of an employee - an employer - is formed here.
Arch.Design thus ranks among Czech companies that offer a significant benefit in hiring new employees, are family-friendly and through this program strengthened personnel marketing.
The house of the bones fascinates even after 100 years. Take a look at Gaudí’s interiors
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the staircase resembles the spine of the dinosaur, and the balconies are open to fish mouth.
This is the house of Casa Batlló in Barcelona by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Thanks to its organic shapes, the house has earned the nickname House of Bones.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stone, fragments of tiles and mosaic, a facade resembling scales and ubiquitous soft curves, all this is typical of the Art Nouveau Antoni Gaudí.
The facade of the house is played by dream lines, tender colors and textures resembling nature and animals.
In the detailed observation, you can see the geometry, rhythm and precisely thoughtful order.
At night, the whole facade of the houses sounds even more dramatic, it is illuminated so that the impression of the gloss of colors is further enhanced.
The winding and twisting of shapes with the same degree appears in the interiors.
Wood in the waves copies the window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, peepholes and skirting boards.
Batlló House, which stands in the Eixample district on the bustling shopping street Passeig de Grácia No. 43, was created by the reconstruction of a house from 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
The reconstruction took place for two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, originally insisted on demolishing the old building and building a completely new one, but soon accepted Gaudí's idea for an unusual and cheaper redevelopment.
The apartment building Casa Batlló was not proposed by Antoni Gaudí himself.
He was co-operated by architect Josep Maria Jajol.
It was on his designer board that decorations were created for the representative apartment of the owner of the property and the use of a mosaic on the facade.
A number of other artists worked on the facade.
Joint work on the designs of the house Casa Batlló started the successful cooperation of Jejola with Gaudí.
Jjol was involved in the construction of Gaudí's Casa Milá house and Güell Park, which includes Gaudí's other works.
From the locals, the house soon after its completion earned the nickname "House of Bones".
Others, because of the specific mechanism of opening windows, began to call it "the yawning house".
It is also said that at the top of the building is the sword of St. George, the patron saint of Catalonia.
Hidden religious motifs also contain other sculptural elements of the building.
Gaudí designed a unique central heating system for his time with ventilation vents and typical chimneys.
Bizarre may seem their forty-five-degree inclination.
In the creation of Gaudí absolutely disrespected the building regulations of the time and did not allow himself to be bound by them.
At the beginning of the construction, it obtained a building permit from the city, but the data on the planned reconstruction were so vague that two years later during the completion, the city council was terrified by the result and asked for a remedy.
Councillors were bothered, for example, by the fact that the building also interfered with the pillars and the public pavement.
Remediation never happened, on the contrary: only fifteen days after the call of the city district, Josep Batlló applied (and successfully obtained) permission to lease the two highest floors of the building.
The owner himself moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a social lounge and on the third floor of the bedroom and private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented by a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey house intersects a staircase, which can climb up to the roof terrace itself.
The essential elements of the reconstruction were the abolition of all the right angles and straight lines and their replacement with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with a modern concept of interconnecting space.
The social part can be completely connected by opening a lounge door, and a larger company can communicate comfortably without maintaining the privacy needed for more intimate conversations at the same time.
In addition to the new facade, the house with Gaudí’s reconstruction also acquired an unconventional roofing and two extra floors.
Gaudí’s play with light, blue and white glazed tiles, which are clad the inner courtyard and skylights, is also impressive.
The game of two colors gives maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was enough to simply bet on the principle that white reflects light more than dark, which, on the contrary, absorbed by the sun's rays.
The Casa Batlló House, which was included in the UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2005, can be visited by anyone.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and opulent apartment open to the public.
The owners decided to do this step only in 2002, on the occasion of the celebration of the centenary of the birth of the famous creator.
They remained in the tours because they found out that it was a very advantageous business and, in addition, the tours were extended by common and attic spaces, including the roof terrace.
Admission to the monument is definitely not negligible, it is 16.50 euros and students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist cards have a 20 percent discount.
The sum greatly exceeds the price of admission to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to taste the true atmosphere of the house with dragon towers, you need to quickly befriend one of the residents of the apartment building and visit it directly at home.
