More and more parents want to track people, so they want to guard their children
Fear for your own child is bringing more and more people to the idea of GPS babysitting.
The system originally created for the search for cars can also monitor the movement of people, and thus help, for example, in cases such as the disappearance of nine-year-old Anička Janatková.
The device is so far about a size like a box from matches, but soon it can only be as big as a watch.
Many people were frightened by the case of the missing Anička and began to look for the means to better protect their children.
Even at the cost of invading their privacy.
"We try to tell everyone that this is not a spying, but another means to reduce the likelihood that a tragedy will happen," says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, which is one of the suppliers of surveillance equipment to the Czech market.
"I admit that in some cases, such devices can be misused, such as if they put in a bag for someone who doesn't know about it, but we haven't encountered such a case yet."
"Mostly, customers actually buy it for security reasons," Pilin added.
According to him, the child should always know for what purpose the "box" serves and how it is used in an emergency.
Children's psychologist Dana Bočková points out that if a child does not want to wear anything like that, she will simply get rid of it.
"Even very young children are showing great creativity in how to intentionally lose some things when they don't want to be under control."
"Various expectations were previously raised by mobile phones, which, however, can be turned off as well as these tracking devices," Bočková said.
According to her, it is also questionable whether such a device would actually help in the event of an attack.
"As far as the abduction is under preparation, the perpetrator will practically always ensure that the child does not have any electronics on him that could reveal his position."
"Now it's the phone."
"When the tracking devices start expanding, they will look for them as well, because their sale will certainly be supported by massive advertising."
"In that case, criminals will always be one step ahead of the police," says the psychologist.
However, he admits that a similar device can help in the event of an unnecessary pedophile attack.
According to Robert Cech of RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both cars and people, even if the surveillance equipment is immediately destroyed after the attack occurs, its presence may help.
"The device can be set to regularly send position after a certain period of time."
"If it is damaged, at least the last position of the person concerned will be available."
"The more expensive devices have built-in and tiltometers, so even if a person just slips and remains motionlessly lying down, the device will immediately send a warning with the location," Čech said.
According to him, a similar service can be done by smartphones with navigation, where you just need to upload special software.
The problem with current tracking units is that they are either devices similar to pendants the size of a matchbox or smaller mobile phones.
This is always the risk of losing them.
According to Pilin from Macro Weil, this is now testing a device that looks like a regular digital watch.
