Longer forefinger than ring finger is a lower risk of cancer
Men who have index finger longer than a ring finger are at a lower risk of getting prostate cancer.
This is a surprising conclusion to a study published by the British Cancer Journal on Wednesday.
It may be related to the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our results show that the relative length of the finger can serve as a simple test of the risk of prostate cancer, especially for men under 60," said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should undergo a test for prostate cancer, especially in combination with a genetic risk or other threatening factors such as family health burden, Eeles added.
In the period 1994-2009, she and her colleagues in Britain followed more than 1,500 patients with prostate cancer patients and concurrently over three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had their index finger on their right hand shorter than the ring finger.
They were the same probability of prostate cancer as 19 percent of those whose fingers were the same length.
However, in the case of those who had a index finger longer than the ring finger, this risk fell by 33 percent, for men up to sixty, the decrease was even 87 percent.
The ratio of length of the two mentioned fingers - formed in the prenatal period - apparently reflects the different levels of sex hormones to which the child is exposed in the uterus.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index finger.
Earlier research has shown that testosterone supports growing prostate cancer.
The leading Czech geneticist and former chairman of the Academy of Sciences, Professor Václav Pačes, told the Czech News Agency that he clearly knows about this study, but it does not seem to him that the relationship between the length of his fingers and cancer is "present".
