Support for democracy in Latin America is growing, as is the promotion of private enterprise.
Crime is more concerned than unemployment.
And Brazil sees many regions more influential than the United States.
These are some of the results of the current Latinobarómetra survey, which was held in 18 countries and published exclusively in The Economist.
Since the survey has been held regularly since 1995, it can monitor changes in attitudes across the region.
Two related items dominate in this year’s survey, which took place in September and early October.
The first is that Latin America is in a fairly cheerful mood.
The second is to increase the stability of attitudes towards democracy and its key institutions.
Support for democracy in several countries on the outskirts of the Pacific in South America has increased significantly (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has averaged 6% a year since 2002, democracy support has risen from a low of 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It also grew up in Mexico, where economics was recovering after a deep decline in production last year.
But only about half of those surveyed in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous areas, are convinced Democrats, which is withdrawing the regional average (see chart 2).
About 44% of respondents across the area expressed satisfaction with how democracy works in practice in their country, it is the same number as last year, but compared to 2001, when it was 25%, it is a big increase (graf 3).
Roughly 34% said they trusted the Diet in their country and 45% trust the government, again the same numbers as last year, but this is a big difference compared to 2003 (17% and 24%).
Ten years ago, the economic crisis undermined democracy in Latin America.
The support arose during the global financial crisis probably because many Latin American countries suffered only a short recession and enjoyed a strong recovery.
In addition, a stronger social security network has helped protect poor people.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America announced this week that the ratio of Latino-borne people living in poverty increased only slightly in 2009 and fell again to 32% this year.)
But the mood varies in a wide range from country to ground (see Graph 4).
Brazil’s strong economic performance and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, are reflected in a widely accepted sense of progress.
This situation is rareer in Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more serious and the state of violent crime deteriorated.
For the second time since surveys began to be conducted, more respondents across Latin America see the crime rather than unemployment as the most important issue (see Chart 5).
Roughly 31% say that either they themselves or their close relatives were the victim of a crime last year, but this is a decrease compared to an figure of 38% from last year and is also the lowest number since 1995.
More massive economic performance is reflected in the growing support for private entrepreneurship and market economy: around 71% of respondents across the region say that private enterprise is essential for development, this percentage increased from 56% of 2007 (see Chart 6).
About 58% agree that the market economy is the only system that will allow their country to develop, this percentage has grown from 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela have the same opinion (and 80% support private business there), although their left-wing president Hugo Chávez expropriate many private firms.
Brazil is a country that has a leader in the area, as 19% of respondents mentioned (compared to 18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, unchanged compared to last year) and Venezuela (9%, compared to 11% last year)
However, the United States is considered the most influential country by respondents in Mexico and in much of Central America, with Venezuela enjoying success in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
