Sport and circumvention of the rules
The tricks, such as Alonso and Ramos in the match with Ajax, show wits, not the intention to escape punishment.
The supposedly orchestrated exclusion of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the Champions League match against Ajax on November 23 caused a sea of ink to be listed about whether this is unsportsmanlike conduct, and whether UEFA should not punish both footballers.
As is known, a few minutes before the end of the match (which their team had clearly won) the appointed players deliberately lost time one by one the moment when the foul was to be played to provoke the judge, and he showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, the two players will deliver the prescribed penalty in the following match against Auxerre - with Real Madrid ending in their group in the lead - and they will be able, deprived of their cards, to the next stage.
In the end, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee gave coach Jose Mourinho a penalty for two matches and guilty players were fined in cash.
Provoking a yellow card under similar conditions is not a new practice, but it is more or less common in football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos of football, that is, rules that are unspeld, but follow.
Part of the discussion in this case arose thanks to the fact that it was the Real Madrid team (which boasts generosity and honor in its anthem, and which has already been fined by its players for similar actions), and it seems, also thanks to the dramatization led by Mourinho, which thus adds another episode to its long history of the comedian and provocateur.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this kind of conduct, which is not explicitly prohibited by the rules, is contrary to the principles of sport, i.e. whether these acts are circumvented by law; these are indeed actions respecting sporting rules, the meaning of which, however, it seems to be trying to circumvent.
It is addressed what type of damage such conduct acts in the sporting spirit.
One of the essentials of sporting behavior is the physical inviolability of opponents, which has not been violated in these cases, i.e. there was no violent game.
Another of these essentials characterizing a clean game is to avoid that players, thanks to their offense, have an advantage over the opponent's team - which also did not happen here.
Thus, the paradoxical event of the Real Madrid players is the fact that what we normally characterize as a lest or circumvention of the law, there was no hidden violation of the rules in order to avoid sanction, but this behavior should have been as evident as possible in order to receive the punishment.
They waited and they were happy to get the punishment.
Another question, however, is what advantage the culprits will have of their intentional offense.
Here it is necessary to state that the opponent does not get into a disadvantaged position, and that he will not achieve any benefit in the current match, because the evident consequence is that the team itself will have fewer players.
And even this is not a useful strategy for the next match, as the club will not be able to count on these players.
The advantage obviously lies in that players will begin the next phase of the Champions League without cards, which could jeopardize their participation in the future match.
However, this is an advantage in the long term and with a certain degree of uncertainty, i.e. at first glance, the team can be eliminated, and in addition, players will receive a penalty, and they will go to the second round of cards, in which one less card is sufficient to exclude them than in the first round.
So, as the wheels continue, it will not be entirely clear whether this is an advantage.
In short, these negotiations do not go against the sporting spirit, which includes strategic decisions that will allow maximum benefit to be obtained under the rules.
in the case we deal with here, players did not aim to avoid the penalty (which would be a clear case of circumvention of the rules), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without avoiding or fleeing from punishment.
Although the line between wit and circumventing the rules is not entirely clear, I believe that in this case it was clearly a wit.
It seems to me that the controversy arises for two reasons: because it was two self-exclusion and because of the way the transmission of instructions to their provocation from the leadership took place.
Damage to sporting principles by these events is not as ethical as aesthetic.
