The United States is Changing Visa Rules
People will have to contact the Visa Applicant Services Centres before the audition at the Consular Department; the costs will be lower and the waiting time will be reduced.
From 10 January 2011, the process of discussing visas will change at the Embassy of the United States and Consulates.
with the new procedure, most applicants will have to contact the Visa Applicant Services center (abbreviated from ASC English) before the interview at the Consular Department.
The ASC staff will remove the applicant's biometric information and they will be evaluated by the Consular Unit before the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages, including the following:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, it will no longer be necessary to pay a fee for the agreement of the meeting, the second for processing the application and another for the delivery of the document by the transport service.
The applicant shall pay only one fee, which will cover all three services.
The current tariff will remain unchanged: the amount equivalent to $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa cases with applications (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for a visa for merchants and investors.
People who want to renew their visa will not have to interview a consular officer, but only turn to the nearest ASC, where they submit their papers and fingerprints will be taken away from them.
Since biometric information will be taken away from the ASC, applicants who will require a second meeting with an interview at the Consular Department will spend less time here than in the past.
Likewise, those who will apply for a visa at the Consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay an extra service fee of $26.
For more information on the new visa application procedure, please visit the following website http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boleines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
