Climate: how France hacked its funding promises
A year after the Copenhagen Accord, it is time to try to keep promises for quickly unblocked financing (meaning fast start financing (fast start) or premature), implemented by developed countries.
And big French hacks have been detected
In the Copenhagen Accord, developed countries pledged to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has pledged €7.2 billion for three years and France €1.26 billion (i.e., 420 million per year).
At the launch of the COP16, the EU pulled out a large ace to convince its partners of the reality of its fast start financing commitment: a report specifying the actions of its Member States, a press conference, a grand side event, the distribution of brochures...
A transparent operation invaluable and valued at its true value: developed countries and civil society would like all developed countries and civil society to do them the same and with the same degree of accuracy.
The EU announces that it released €2.2 billion in 2010 and is bringing it on the right path to keeping its promise of $7.2 billion in 2012.
But if we focus on the detail, we find that things are much more complicated.
These funds are "new and additional" under the Copenhagen Agreement to ensure that the increased burden is realised without harming Public Assistance for Development.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission has proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the process.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission considered the year 2009 as a reference: international funding has been preserved and it adds 150 million to three years of fast start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar references with annual payment dates or deadlines at the level of public aid for development.
France, on the other hand, believes that the financing of "all new projects" of 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to the expenditure of previous periods or the Global Level of Public Assistance for the Development of d'Aide publique au Developpement.
Specifically, the total amount of support for France towards developing countries may remain constant (or even reduce) to comply with its commitment to the financing of "new and additional "...
Another crucial element is the division into donations and loans.
There is no rule there yet, and everyone chooses their own method of calculation.
Some, such as France, they consider that 1€ borrowed equals 1€ donated.
Evidently, this is difficult to prove: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be documented for some investments that are profitable (often projects related to reducing emissions consisting of more efficient technologies), it is foolish to present one euro that we get, as the equivalent of one euro that we give... , we should not understand it by virtue of our obligations, but as the price of a loan for a lending country (i.e. the equivalent of the interest rate).
But France can only give such a reason: it "teats" its commitment of 420 million euros, of which 91.5% makes a loan ($389.8 million) and 8.5% donations (€36.1 million) - see the EU document so that you can verify this yourself.
It is the only country in the Union that uses a loan on such a scale.
Germany has claimed 46% from there, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) comply with their obligations with 100% donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union gives 1€ to satisfy its promise, France will give only 10 centimeters and consider this effort to be comparable.
Beautiful juggler piece!
To summarise, in its financing of the "fast start" France operates with double swindling: on the one hand, with the development of the stock over time and on the other hand with a real financial burden.
Although it spends only 36.1 million euros, it can convince that it is issuing 420 million euros of "new and additional" in connection with its promises.
The manipulation of the finance minister (since it seems that although it is Bercy, who made such decisions) could have a double negative impact, at the same time within the EU (why would the member states continue to donate when it is enough to lend?) and in negotiations, because developing countries are not entirely naive...
The chapter of early funding is just a small question, relatively short-term, in relation to a series of climate discussions.
But it could be a grain of sand in a huge machine like the UNFCCC.
Let's hope that's not our case.
Whatever it is, it is necessary to draw knowledge from this first year of early funding.
First, France should announce the change in its manner of keeping accounting records for 2011 and 2012, in the spirit of respecting its obligations and deference and fairness to other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France should avoid discussions about deposits in long-term financing (another fundamental chapter currently discussed): we will not escape the question of "additionality" or the way loans are paid in.
France should change its position to become as progressive for these deposits as for others.
